If I forget, remind me.

269
00:13:20,802 --> 00:13:22,302
But it's almost always the case

270
00:13:22,302 --> 00:13:23,802
that it will be summed over,

271
00:13:23,802 --> 00:13:27,802
so that i is really just a summation index.

272
00:13:27,802 --> 00:13:30,802
It's, you can call it j if you like.

273
00:13:30,802 --> 00:13:31,802
It doesn't matter.

274
00:13:31,802 --> 00:13:32,802
All right, let's check this out.

275
00:13:32,802 --> 00:13:34,802
Let's see if this makes sense.

276
00:13:36,802 --> 00:13:39,302
So I can rewrite this by just

277
00:13:39,302 --> 00:13:41,802
shifting this factor over to this side.

278
00:13:41,802 --> 00:13:44,802
Let me do it.

279
00:13:44,802 --> 00:13:45,802
Now let's rewrite it.

280
00:13:45,802 --> 00:13:55,802
i, psi m i, i psi.

281
00:13:55,802 --> 00:13:57,802
Now you have to remember the rule.

282
00:13:57,802 --> 00:14:00,302
Whenever you see i and i

283
00:14:00,302 --> 00:14:02,802
back to back like this, summed over,

284
00:14:02,802 --> 00:14:04,802
that's the unit matrix.

285
00:14:04,802 --> 00:14:06,802
That's the unit operator.

286
00:14:06,802 --> 00:14:11,802
The sum of i, i is the unit matrix.

287
00:14:11,802 --> 00:14:13,802
It can always be canceled out.

288
00:14:13,802 --> 00:14:15,802
It's just the unit matrix.

289
00:14:15,802 --> 00:14:16,802
It makes no difference.

290
00:14:16,802 --> 00:14:19,802
You can just remove it, and the

291
00:14:19,802 --> 00:14:22,802
result is that it's psi m psi.

292
00:14:22,802 --> 00:14:24,802
Well, that's not too surprising.

293
00:14:24,802 --> 00:14:28,302
The average of m is the expectation value

294
00:14:28,302 --> 00:14:31,802
of m, if you have a pure state.

295
00:14:31,802 --> 00:14:35,802
Now, supposing you don't have a pure state.

296
00:14:35,802 --> 00:14:37,802
Let's suppose we don't have a pure.

297
00:14:37,802 --> 00:14:38,802
Question?

298
00:14:38,802 --> 00:14:39,802
Should that be m bar?

299
00:14:39,802 --> 00:14:41,802
Yeah, this.

300
00:14:41,802 --> 00:14:43,802
No, sorry.

301
00:14:43,802 --> 00:14:44,802
m bar up here, yes.

302
00:14:44,802 --> 00:14:45,802
Thank you.

303
00:14:45,802 --> 00:14:48,802
Very good.

304
00:14:48,802 --> 00:14:52,802
Yep.

305
00:14:52,802 --> 00:14:55,802
OK, let's take a more general case

306
00:14:55,802 --> 00:14:58,802
when we don't have a pure state.

307
00:14:58,802 --> 00:15:02,802
And we'll see what we get.

308
00:15:02,802 --> 00:15:04,802
But let's evaluate it.

309
00:15:04,802 --> 00:15:08,802
Let's see.

310
00:15:08,802 --> 00:15:12,802
Yeah.

311
00:15:12,802 --> 00:15:14,802
OK, so again, we have

312
00:15:14,802 --> 00:15:16,802
to take trace of rho m.

313
00:15:16,802 --> 00:15:19,802
But let's do the calculation in

314
00:15:19,802 --> 00:15:22,802
the basis in which rho is diagonal.

315
00:15:22,802 --> 00:15:23,802
All right?

316
00:15:23,802 --> 00:15:27,302
So to calculate the trace, we put

317
00:15:27,302 --> 00:15:30,802
i rho m i summed over i.

318
00:15:30,802 --> 00:15:32,802
I'm not going to write a summation sign.

319
00:15:32,802 --> 00:15:34,802
OK.

320
00:15:34,802 --> 00:15:36,802
I'm going to suppress the summation sign for now.

321
00:15:36,802 --> 00:15:38,802
Just summed over i.

322
00:15:38,802 --> 00:15:41,802
But now we can insert a complete

323
00:15:41,802 --> 00:15:44,802
set of states between rho and m.

324
00:15:44,802 --> 00:15:48,802
This is a trick we constantly keep doing.

325
00:15:48,802 --> 00:15:51,802
In order to reduce the calculation to something

326
00:15:51,802 --> 00:15:54,802
involving matrix elements of both rho and m,

327
00:15:54,802 --> 00:15:58,802
we stick in between there a complete set of states.

328
00:15:58,802 --> 00:16:00,802
And we write it in the form i.

329
00:16:00,802 --> 00:16:02,802
Maybe, I guess I'll put the sum.

330
00:16:02,802 --> 00:16:04,802
Sum on i.

331
00:16:04,802 --> 00:16:10,802
i i rho m.

332
00:16:10,802 --> 00:16:13,302
But I'm going to insert

333
00:16:13,302 --> 00:16:15,802
in here a sum over j.

334
00:16:15,802 --> 00:16:20,802
And now it's a sum over both i and j.

335
00:16:20,802 --> 00:16:23,802
Now, if I'm working in the

336
00:16:23,802 --> 00:16:26,802
basis in which rho is diagonal,

337
00:16:26,802 --> 00:16:28,802
then I know what the

338
00:16:28,802 --> 00:16:30,802
matrix element i rho j is.

339
00:16:30,802 --> 00:16:34,802
This is just these i rho j.

340
00:16:34,802 --> 00:16:35,802
What is that?

341
00:16:35,802 --> 00:16:37,802
That's just the matrix.

342
00:16:37,802 --> 00:16:39,802
It has an i index and a j index.

343
00:16:39,802 --> 00:16:41,802
The row or the column,

344
00:16:41,802 --> 00:16:43,802
let's see, which one is which?

345
00:16:43,802 --> 00:16:47,802
This one is...

346
00:16:47,802 --> 00:16:49,802
i is the row.

347
00:16:49,802 --> 00:16:50,802
And it says here the

348
00:16:50,802 --> 00:16:51,802
row and j is the column?

349
00:16:51,802 --> 00:16:52,802
Whichever.

350
00:16:52,802 --> 00:16:53,802
Yeah.

351
00:16:53,802 --> 00:16:56,802
j would be the column.

352
00:16:56,802 --> 00:16:57,802
j is the column, I think.

353
00:16:57,802 --> 00:16:58,802
Yeah.

354
00:16:58,802 --> 00:16:59,802
Right.

355
00:16:59,802 --> 00:17:00,802
OK.

356
00:17:00,802 --> 00:17:04,301
But since rho is diagonal, this object here only

357
00:17:04,301 --> 00:17:07,801
has a matrix element if i is equal to j.

358
00:17:07,801 --> 00:17:10,801
And then the matrix element is just lambda.

359
00:17:10,801 --> 00:17:12,801
Lambda j.

360
00:17:12,801 --> 00:17:14,801
The eigenvalue.

361
00:17:14,801 --> 00:17:15,801
If...

362
00:17:15,801 --> 00:17:18,801
So the sum over i and j

363
00:17:18,801 --> 00:17:21,801
becomes a sum only over one of them.

364
00:17:21,801 --> 00:17:24,801
And let's take it to be j because

365
00:17:24,801 --> 00:17:27,801
i has to equal j because rho is diagonal.

366
00:17:27,801 --> 00:17:28,802
And then we have...

367
00:17:28,802 --> 00:17:32,802
j m j.

368
00:17:32,802 --> 00:17:34,802
I've put j here because i

369
00:17:34,802 --> 00:17:36,802
has to equal j in the sum.

370
00:17:36,802 --> 00:17:37,802
Well, what is this?

371
00:17:37,802 --> 00:17:39,802
This is just the expectation value

372
00:17:39,802 --> 00:17:41,802
of m in the j-th state.

373
00:17:41,802 --> 00:17:45,802
This is just the probability of the j-th state.

374
00:17:45,802 --> 00:17:48,802
So this reads exactly what you might expect.

375
00:17:48,802 --> 00:17:53,302
It's the average of m in the j-th state weighed

376
00:17:53,302 --> 00:17:57,802
with the probability, which is the probability of the j-th state.

377
00:17:57,802 --> 00:18:04,802
So you can think of the eigenvalues of rho as the probabilities to be

378
00:18:04,802 --> 00:18:11,802
in the j-th state, but only in the basis in which rho is diagonal.

379
00:18:11,802 --> 00:18:12,802
Yeah.

380
00:18:12,802 --> 00:18:13,802
Is that really j and j

381
00:18:13,802 --> 00:18:14,802
instead of j and i there?

382
00:18:14,802 --> 00:18:16,802
Yes, because i has to be equal to j.

383
00:18:16,802 --> 00:18:18,802
Otherwise, you don't get anything.

384
00:18:18,802 --> 00:18:20,802
Right.

385
00:18:20,802 --> 00:18:22,802
So for trivial reasons, it is.

386
00:18:27,802 --> 00:18:30,802
You're still summing over i, right?

387
00:18:30,802 --> 00:18:33,802
You're still summing over j here.

388
00:18:33,802 --> 00:18:38,802
Over j.

389
00:18:38,802 --> 00:18:40,802
Right.

390
00:18:40,802 --> 00:18:41,802
Yeah.

391
00:18:41,802 --> 00:18:42,802
Here I really broke my own rule.

392
00:18:42,802 --> 00:18:45,802
This thing is repeated three times.

393
00:18:45,802 --> 00:18:47,802
Right.

394
00:18:47,802 --> 00:18:48,802
Okay.

395
00:18:48,802 --> 00:18:53,802
Those are the rules about density matrices.

396
00:18:53,802 --> 00:18:56,802
Let me remind you of one more definition.

397
00:18:56,802 --> 00:19:01,802
If you're given a probability distribution, probabilities, let's

398
00:19:01,802 --> 00:19:06,802
say p sub i, this is classical probabilities now,

399
00:19:06,802 --> 00:19:13,302
p sub i, the i-th probability for the i-th

400
00:19:13,302 --> 00:19:19,802
possibility, then the entropy is defined S, S for entropy.

401
00:19:19,802 --> 00:19:21,802
I don't know why they chose S.

402
00:19:21,802 --> 00:19:22,802
Why it's not E?

403
00:19:22,802 --> 00:19:25,802
Probably E because you're confused with energy.

404
00:19:26,802 --> 00:19:32,802
S for entropy is equal by definition.

405
00:19:32,802 --> 00:19:34,802
This is the definition of it.

406
00:19:34,802 --> 00:19:36,802
But we can say what it means roughly.

407
00:19:36,802 --> 00:19:43,802
It's again the sum over all of the possible configurations or all of

408
00:19:43,802 --> 00:19:50,802
the possible possibilities of minus p sub i times logarithm of p sub i.

409
00:19:50,802 --> 00:19:54,802
That's its definition.

410
00:19:54,802 --> 00:19:55,802
Again.

411
00:19:55,802 --> 00:19:58,802
If only one of the p's is

412
00:19:58,802 --> 00:20:01,802
non-zero, then it's got to be one.

413
00:20:01,802 --> 00:20:03,802
All right.

414
00:20:03,802 --> 00:20:05,802
Logarithm of one is zero.

415
00:20:05,802 --> 00:20:09,802
On the other hand, all the other p's are zero.

416
00:20:09,802 --> 00:20:13,802
So in that case, if you have

417
00:20:13,802 --> 00:20:17,802
complete knowledge, then the entropy is zero.

418
00:20:17,802 --> 00:20:20,802
So zero entropy means complete knowledge.

419
00:20:20,802 --> 00:20:22,802
You know precisely that the probability

420
00:20:22,802 --> 00:20:24,802
distribution is peaked at one particular point.

421
00:20:24,802 --> 00:20:26,802
Zero everywhere else.

422
00:20:26,802 --> 00:20:32,802
The other extreme is when you have complete ignorance.

423
00:20:32,802 --> 00:20:35,302
And in that case, each p

424
00:20:35,302 --> 00:20:37,802
sub i is one over n.

425
00:20:37,802 --> 00:20:39,802
Let's take it to be the same n here.

426
00:20:39,802 --> 00:20:43,802
Each p sub i is one over n.

427
00:20:43,802 --> 00:20:47,802
And then you get S is equal to, before you

428
00:20:47,802 --> 00:20:51,802
do the sum, one over n log one over n.

429
00:20:51,802 --> 00:20:52,802
But it's minus log one over n.

430
00:20:52,802 --> 00:20:53,802
So that's actually one over n.

431
00:20:53,802 --> 00:20:57,802
So that's actually the same as log of n.

432
00:20:57,802 --> 00:21:00,802
But then you have n terms in the sum.

433
00:21:00,802 --> 00:21:03,802
So you have to multiply this by n.

434
00:21:03,802 --> 00:21:06,802
And the answer is that the entropy

435
00:21:06,802 --> 00:21:09,802
is logarithm of the number of states.

436
00:21:09,802 --> 00:21:12,302
The entropy is, roughly speaking, the

437
00:21:12,302 --> 00:21:14,802
logarithm of the number of states

438
00:21:14,802 --> 00:21:20,802
which are important in the probability distribution.

439
00:21:20,802 --> 00:21:21,802
That's as close as I can get

440
00:21:21,802 --> 00:21:22,802
to give you a definition in words.

441
00:21:22,802 --> 00:21:26,802
But you don't need a definition in words.

442
00:21:26,802 --> 00:21:29,802
This is precisely what it is.

443
00:21:29,802 --> 00:21:31,802
But nevertheless, it is true that

444
00:21:31,802 --> 00:21:33,802
if you have a probability distribution

445
00:21:33,802 --> 00:21:37,802
which has fairly large over some set of states

446
00:21:37,802 --> 00:21:40,802
and then pretty damn small everywhere else,

447
00:21:40,802 --> 00:21:43,302
that the answer for the entropy will

448
00:21:43,302 --> 00:21:45,802
essentially be logarithm of the number of states

449
00:21:45,802 --> 00:21:49,802
for which the probability distribution is significant.

450
00:21:49,802 --> 00:21:50,802
So it's a measure of the degree of probability distribution.

451
00:21:50,802 --> 00:21:53,802
It's a measure of the degree of ignorance.

452
00:21:53,802 --> 00:21:56,802
The more ignorance, in other words, the more

453
00:21:56,802 --> 00:21:59,802
states that the probability distribution is spread out over,

454
00:21:59,802 --> 00:22:02,802
the less you know about the system.

455
00:22:02,802 --> 00:22:05,802
The more you know about the system, the

456
00:22:05,802 --> 00:22:08,802
fewer the states, and the smaller the entropy.

457
00:22:08,802 --> 00:22:12,802
So it's a measure of ignorance.

458
00:22:12,802 --> 00:22:16,802
Or a measure of, well, yeah.

459
00:22:16,802 --> 00:22:19,802
Now we want to come to entanglement.

460
00:22:20,802 --> 00:22:25,802
Entanglement happens when we have more than one system.

461
00:22:25,802 --> 00:22:28,302
So let's suppose we have

462
00:22:28,302 --> 00:22:30,802
a system composed of two parts.

463
00:22:34,802 --> 00:22:38,802
And let's suppose we have some basis.

464
00:22:38,802 --> 00:22:42,802
And the basis is labeled

465
00:22:42,802 --> 00:22:46,802
by a state or an observable,

466
00:22:46,802 --> 00:22:48,802
A for one of the

467
00:22:48,802 --> 00:22:50,802
subsystems and B for the other.

468
00:22:50,802 --> 00:22:53,302
Now for the case of two spins,

469
00:22:53,302 --> 00:22:55,802
A and B could be up and,

470
00:22:55,802 --> 00:22:57,802
A and B would both be up and down.

471
00:22:57,802 --> 00:22:59,302
We could have up, up,

472
00:22:59,302 --> 00:23:00,802
up, down, down, up, down, down.

473
00:23:00,802 --> 00:23:06,802
Other possibilities, we could have a spin with two states

474
00:23:06,802 --> 00:23:10,802
and an atom with four states or three states.

475
00:23:10,802 --> 00:23:12,802
In that case, A would go from

476
00:23:12,802 --> 00:23:14,802
one to two or up and down.

477
00:23:14,802 --> 00:23:16,802
B would run over one

478
00:23:16,802 --> 00:23:18,802
to three or one to four.

479
00:23:18,802 --> 00:23:22,802
And so altogether, the total number of states

480
00:23:22,802 --> 00:23:26,802
would be the product of the number of configurations

481
00:23:26,802 --> 00:23:30,802
of the subsystem A times the number of subsystem B.

482
00:23:30,802 --> 00:23:32,802
So if we had a spin which

483
00:23:32,802 --> 00:23:34,802
could be in one of two directions,

484
00:23:34,802 --> 00:23:37,802
and we were putting it together with an atom

485
00:23:37,802 --> 00:23:39,802
which could be in three possible states,

486
00:23:39,802 --> 00:23:41,802
the total number of states would be six,

487
00:23:41,802 --> 00:23:43,802
but it would just be three times two.

488
00:23:43,802 --> 00:23:44,802
Okay.

489
00:23:44,802 --> 00:23:47,802
Let's, let's say that A, little a,

490
00:23:48,802 --> 00:23:52,802
runs from one to capital N,

491
00:23:52,802 --> 00:23:55,802
and little b runs from one to little n.

492
00:23:55,802 --> 00:23:57,802
They don't have to be the same.

493
00:23:57,802 --> 00:24:00,802
They could be two quite different systems.

494
00:24:00,802 --> 00:24:02,802
Okay.

495
00:24:02,802 --> 00:24:05,802
Then the most general state of the combined system

496
00:24:05,802 --> 00:24:10,802
that we can write is a sum.

497
00:24:10,802 --> 00:24:14,802
And we're going to sum over A and B

498
00:24:14,802 --> 00:24:18,802
of some set of coefficients,

499
00:24:18,802 --> 00:24:20,802
called a wave function,

500
00:24:20,802 --> 00:24:23,802
of A and B, function of A and B.

501
00:24:23,802 --> 00:24:25,802
Now A and B are discrete,

502
00:24:25,802 --> 00:24:27,802
or at least for us now,

503
00:24:27,802 --> 00:24:31,802
A and B are discrete variables.

504
00:24:31,802 --> 00:24:33,802
In a more general context,

505
00:24:33,802 --> 00:24:35,802
A and B could, might even be continuous,

506
00:24:35,802 --> 00:24:37,802
but for our studies here,

507
00:24:37,802 --> 00:24:42,802
where we're studying qubits and discrete systems,

508
00:24:42,802 --> 00:24:44,802
A and B run over integers.

509
00:24:44,802 --> 00:24:47,802
They're integer valued variables,

510
00:24:47,802 --> 00:24:50,802
but we can still write psi of A and B,

511
00:24:50,802 --> 00:24:52,802
sticking in any pair of integers,

512
00:24:52,802 --> 00:24:54,802
that gives us a complex number,

513
00:24:54,802 --> 00:24:57,802
multiplied by the state vector A, B,

514
00:24:57,802 --> 00:24:58,802
summed over A and B.

515
00:24:58,802 --> 00:25:01,802
That's the most general state we can write down.

516
00:25:01,802 --> 00:25:03,802
If we want to normalize it,

517
00:25:03,802 --> 00:25:04,802
which I do,

518
00:25:04,802 --> 00:25:07,802
then we want the sum over A and B

519
00:25:07,802 --> 00:25:10,802
of psi star psi to add up to one.

520
00:25:10,802 --> 00:25:11,802
Okay.

521
00:25:11,802 --> 00:25:13,802
So I won't write that down.

522
00:25:13,802 --> 00:25:15,802
The sum over A and

523
00:25:15,802 --> 00:25:17,802
B of psi star times psi

524
00:25:17,802 --> 00:25:19,802
should be equal to one.

525
00:25:19,802 --> 00:25:22,802
And that's our normalization condition.

526
00:25:23,802 --> 00:25:24,802
Okay.

527
00:25:24,802 --> 00:25:27,802
Let's now suppose that we're doing an experiment

528
00:25:27,802 --> 00:25:30,802
which does not involve B.

529
00:25:30,802 --> 00:25:31,802
It could be because the two systems

530
00:25:31,802 --> 00:25:34,802
are separated from each other,

531
00:25:34,802 --> 00:25:37,802
and Bob is down at that end of the room.

532
00:25:37,802 --> 00:25:40,802
He doesn't even bother looking at his system at all.

533
00:25:40,802 --> 00:25:42,802
Alice is up at this end,

534
00:25:42,802 --> 00:25:43,802
and Alice is going to do an experiment,

535
00:25:43,802 --> 00:25:45,802
and the experiment is going to involve

536
00:25:45,802 --> 00:25:47,802
only the A degrees of A.

537
00:25:47,802 --> 00:25:50,802
So the A degrees of freedom.

538
00:25:50,802 --> 00:25:52,802
Okay.

539
00:25:52,802 --> 00:25:54,802
The observable that she's going to measure,

540
00:25:54,802 --> 00:25:57,802
let's call it M.

541
00:25:57,802 --> 00:26:06,802
M is an observable

542
00:26:06,802 --> 00:26:14,802
for subsystem A.

